*3. Gauge Theory on the Noncommutative Torus 

Having dispensed with the mathematical formalities, we will now
define classical Yang-Mills theory on the noncommutative torus. We
will argue in this section, at the classical level, that this
noncommutative field theory is an exactly solvable model. We fix a
Heisenberg module  over the algebra 
and consider the affine space  of all compatible
connections on . In string theory, this field theory
describes the low-energy dynamics of a bound state configuration
of  coincident D2-branes which carry  units of D0-brane
vortex charge, in a background -field.

3.1. Definition 

For any , we define the
noncommutative Yang-Mills action S[A]=S[]=12g^2 [_1,_2]^2  ,
 where  is the (dimensionless)
Yang-Mills coupling constant. We will regard ()
as a functional . By using the
operator-field correspondence described in section 2.4, the
formula () and the discussion at the end of
section 2.8, we may write () in a more
conventional field theoretic form as S[A]=12g^2 ^2x ^  _N(F_A(x)+)^2 
,  where F_A=_1A_2-_2A_1+A_1A_2-A_2A_1
 is the noncommutative field strength
of an anti-Hermitian  gauge field  on the torus
. The star-product in () is the
tensor product of the associative star-product corresponding to
the dual noncommutativity parameter () with
ordinary matrix multiplication. This extended star-product is
still associative.

Due to the isomorphism (), in the case of gauge
theory on a Heisenberg module the action may be represented as in
() in terms of star-products of fields on
. This is not  possible on a generic projective
module over the noncommutative torus, in which case one can
generally only use the more abstract definition
() of the field theory. Note that the action
() is quadratic in the field strength and so
the non-local interactions due to the star-product appear
explicitly only in (). This is one of the
properties that will enable an exact solution of the field theory
later on. In () we also see that the central
extension in () has the physical interpretation of
a constant background magnetic flux in the noncommutative field
theory, and thereby plays no role in the local dynamics.

3.2. Gauge Symmetry 

The action () is invariant under any covariant
transformation of the form   UU^ , where  is a unitary operator on ,
U^U=UU^ .  The set
of transformations () form the gauge group 
 of the noncommutative gauge theory.
Infinitesimally, it follows from () that the gauge
group acts on gauge potentials through A  A+_A  ,    _A=[,
