 This enables one to classify objects in the
noncommutative gauge theory which have a direct topological
characterization, such as anomalies and solitonic
configurations .

3.3. Integrability 

The fact that noncommutative gauge theory in two dimensions is an
exactly solvable model is most likely to be connected with the fact
that it is an integrable system. We will now indicate how this may
indeed be the case by showing that Yang-Mills theory on the
projective module  naturally defines an
infinite-dimensional Hamiltonian system . On the affine space
, with tangent space identified as
(), we can define a natural symplectic structure
by the two-form [a,b]=ab  ,   
a,b^1()  .  This form is
clearly non-degenerate. It is also independent of the point
