dropped from the moment map (), thereby
indicating once again its irrelevance with respect to dynamics.

*4. Classical Solutions 

In this section we will come to the crux of our presentation, the
exact solution of the classical noncommutative gauge theory. The
technique we will employ is essentially an algebraic version of
the Atiyah-Bott bundle splitting method for obtaining the
solutions of the Yang-Mills equations on ordinary Riemann
surfaces. It relies heavily on the properties of Heisenberg
modules over the noncommutative torus that we discussed in
section 2. The exact classical solutions of noncommutative gauge theory
on the torus were first constructed in .

4.1. Equations of Motion 

The classical field theory is defined by extremizing the action
functional (). We therefore seek the stationary
points of noncommuative Yang-Mills theory which are determined by
the equation A S[A]=0  .
 By using () this leads to the
noncommutative Yang-Mills equations of motion [,[_1,_2]]=0  .
 Under the operator-field correspondence,
these equations may be cast into a more conventional form as _iF_A+A_iF_A-F_AA_i=0
 for . We seek to characterize all
such critical points of noncommutative gauge theory. This we will
do within a particular homotopy class of the Grassmannian manifold
of projectors of the algebra , characterized by a Heisenberg
module  of topological numbers
 and dimension (). As we will see,
in this case there is a nice topological classification of the
classical solutions on the space  of compatible
connections of the Heisenberg module. In addition, by combining
these results with those of section 3.3, it will follow
immediately that the Yang-Mills action () is a
gauge-equivariant Morse functional on .

4.2. BPS States 

Recall from section 2.8 that a Heisenberg module
 is completely characterized by a
connection  of constant curvature
(,). Such connections trivially
satisfy the equations of motion (), because their
curvatures are proportional to the identity operator on 
and are thereby central. What is striking about the constant
curvature solutions is that they provide the absolute
minimum value of the noncommutative Yang-Mills action
() on the module  ,
S[^c ]=_C  S[]  .
They thereby constitute the stable classical vacuum states of the gauge
theory.
In an appropriate supersymmetric extension of the field theory, constant
curvature connections correspond to  BPS configurations
.

To prove this fact, we use the expansion () of the
field strength to expand the action () about a
constant curvature connection to get S[^c +ta]=S[^c ]+
t^2 2g^2 [^c  , 
