4.4. Partitions 

The conclusions just arrived at in the previous subsection show
that, for all , any solution of the classical equations of
motion for Yang-Mills theory on the projective module
 is completely characterized
by a partition  , which we define as a
collection of integers  satisfying the constraints
p_k-q_k&>&0  ,  _k(p_k-q_k)&=&
p-q ,  _kq_k&=&q  .
In addition, to avoid overcounting, it is sometimes useful to
impose a further ordering constraint 
, and regard any two partitions
as the same if they coincide after rearranging their components
according to this ordering. We may then characterize the
components of a partition by integers  which are defined as the
number of partition components that have the  least
dimension . The integer = _a_a
 is then the total number of components in the
given partition. Note that if  is an irrational number,
then the constraint on the magnetic charges in
() is automatically ensured by the dimension
additivity. This is not the case, however, for rational-valued
noncommutativity parameters. In particular, in the commutative
case  this last constraint distinguishes between
"physical" Yang-Mills theory, which would take into account the
sum over all topological charges  (i.e. all isomorphism
classes of principal  bundles over ), and
Yang-Mills theory defined on a particular projective module. In
the noncommutative setting, only gauge theory on a fixed
projective module appears amenable to an unambiguous definition,
reflecting the loss of structure group in this case.

With this at hand, we can finally evaluate the noncommutative
Yang-Mills action on a classical solution, with corresponding
partition . By using the additivity property
() of the action, the formula () for
the constant curvature of a Heisenberg module, and the
Murray-von Neumann dimension formula
, we easily arrive at
S(,)&=&S[ _k^c _(k) ] &=&2^2 g^2  _k(p_k-q_k)
(q_k p_k-q_k -qp-q )^2  .
From the classical action one can in
fact determine a number of important facts about the critical
point set of noncommutative gauge theory. First of all, it is
straightforward to see that, up to gauge equivalence, the action
() vanishes only  for the trivial
partition  corresponding to the Heisenberg module
 itself. This is equivalent to the statement that
the gauge theory is globally minimized by its constant curvature
connection , as we showed in section 4.2.
Secondly, for any fixed finite action solution of the
noncommutative Yang-Mills equations of motion, it is
straightforward to show from () that each
partition contains finitely many components . This shows
that the number () is indeed finite and permits one
to pick out a minimum dimension submodule  as
explained above. Finally, one can show that the set of values of
the noncommutative Yang-Mills action on the critical point set
(the set of all partitions) is discrete , so that the
action indeed defines a bonafide Morse functional on 
.

*5. Morita Duality 

In noncommutative geometry an important role is played by the
notion of "Morita equivalence" of -algebras. Two algebras
are Morita equivalent if they have the same representation theory.
The one-to-one correspondence between their projective modules
means in particular that they have the same K-theory. In
section 2.8 we in fact encountered a very important case of this
duality for noncommutative tori. Namely, the two algebras
 and , with noncommutativity
parameters related through (), are both
represented on the Heisenberg module  and
commute with each other in the representation. They are therefore
Morita equivalent and in this context  is refered to as a
Morita equivalence bimodule between  and
.

Given that noncommutative gauge theories are constructed from the
representations of the algebra, this equivalence has the potential
of supplying a novel duality relation between field theories
defined on different noncommutative spaces. In fact, this is one
of the reasons for the excitement about noncommutative Yang-Mills
theory. The Morita equivalence between two noncommutative tori
turns out to be equivalent to the fact that the underlying tori
 are related by open string T-duality . The
noncommutative Yang-Mills action is invariant under the
equivalence, provided we use an extended notion of Morita
equivalence known as gauge Morita equivalence. Under the extended
equivalence, not only do we obtain a one-to-one correspondence
between projective modules over different noncommutative tori
associated with different topological numbers, but we also augment
this with transformations of connections between the modules. The
conclusion is then that noncommutative Yang-Mills theory is invariant  under T-duality.
This is in marked contrast to the
situation in ordinary Yang-Mills theory which is not duality
invariant. T-duality invariance is one of the remarkable features
of noncommutative field theories that follow from their origins in
string theory, yet can be defined and analysed within the
framework of quantum field theory. In this final section we will
present the Morita transformation rules and describe various
consequences of them.

The full open string T-duality group on  is
 and it acts on the K-theory ring 
 in a spinor representation, in
precisely the same way in which it acts on the Ramond-Ramond
charges of D-branes. In generic spacetime dimension  this group
is . The special feature of two dimensions is that
there is an isomorphism
SO(2,2,)=SL(2,)SL(2,)  . One of these 
factors is just the geometrical automorphism group of the torus
 which acts by discrete Mobius transformations of its
Teichmuller modulus . It is the same symmetry group that
is present in the commutative case and so will not be discussed
any further. The other  acts on the Kahler modulus
of  and has no counterpart in ordinary geometry. It acts
by discrete Mobius transformations of the noncommutativity
parameter . In fact, a well-known theorem of
noncommutative geometryasserts that two noncommutative tori
 and  are Morita
equivalent if and only if m+n r+s   ,      SL(2,)  . This coincides with the transformation rule for the quantity 
under T-duality , where  is the open string metric and  the
antisymmetric tensor field.

The same transformation sends a projective module  of
topological numbers  over the algebra  to a module
 of topological numbers  over , in such
a way that the pair of K-theory charges transforms as an
 doublet  =    .
 From () and
() it is straightforward to show that the
Murray-von Neumann dimensions () of the modules are
related by  r+s   ,
 and hence that the canonical trace on
 is rescaled as  .
 In particular, the Morita equivalence
bimodule for the Heisenberg modules  and
 can be constructed by quantizing open strings in a
background -field where the strings
stretch from a single D2-brane to a
cluster of  coincident D2-branes carrying  units of D0-brane
charge .

Under the gauge Morita equivalence the field strengths of
connections on the modules  and  are related
through F'_A' =(r+s)^2F_A+2r(r+s) 
.  The invariance of the noncommutative
Yang-Mills action () is then guaranteed by the
transformation properties g'^2 &=&r+s^3g^2  ,
(r+s)^2 .
This mapping exhibits explicitly the
physical roleof the background flux , as it is required to
absorb the inhomogeneous term in the transformation
(). In particular, it can shifted in and out of the
action in a variety of different ways with no effect on the field
theory, thus showing precisely why it had no real bearing on our
previous analyses.

What is particularly important for us is the way that the solution
spaces of two dual gauge theories map into one
another . The Morita transformation acts diagonally on
the critical point sets of noncommutative gauge theories, providing a
one-to-one correspondence between their constant curvature
connections , and hence their classical solutions. This
implies, in particular, that the basic structure of partitions between
dual gauge theories is the same. It is straightforward to check that
the classical action () is invariant under the
transformations (), () and ().
Moreover, in the supersymmetric gauge theory the entire spectrum
of BPS states is invariant under the Morita duality .

Finally, let us note that an ordinary  gauge theory is
mapped to a noncommutative gauge theory with rational-valued
noncommutativity parameter  and Yang-Mills coupling
constant  under the Morita map
() and (). In this way it is
possible to embed ordinary Yang-Mills theory into the wider class
of noncommutative gauge theories, and this embedding has been used
to suggest that noncommutative Yang-Mills theory can be used to
impose very stringent constraints on ordinary large  gauge
theories on tori . In particular, an ordinary  gauge theory
with 't Hooft flux is Morita equivalent to a rational
 noncommutative gauge theory with single-valued gauge
fields . In this way the non-Abelian colour degrees of freedom of
commutative Yang-Mills theory may be traded for spacetime
noncommutativity.

